Our analysis reveals that, like medieval scholastics who privileged authoritative texts over empirical investigation, current AI research tools exhibit a "digital scholasticism" that accepts well-formatted academic sources as inherently authoritative without critical assessment. This technoscholastic worldview explains why systems with access to vast knowledge corpora fail to generate novel insights or identify genuine research gaps. Through concrete case studies—particularly examining Digital Humanities programs in Australia—we document how these tools consistently present defunct initiatives as active, ignore temporal context, and fail to recognise "useful absences" of evidence that would signal program discontinuation to human researchers.

